      <title>Introducing the tidyr pivot_longer()</title>
      <link>/post/introducing-the-tidyr-pivot-longer/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/post/introducing-the-tidyr-pivot-longer/</guid>
      <description>


&lt;p&gt;When working with a dataframe, it‚Äôs usually preferable that you respect the philosophy introduced by &lt;a href=&#34;https://vita.had.co.nz/papers/tidy-data.pdf&#34;&gt;Hadley Wickham&lt;/a&gt; about the &lt;strong&gt;Tidy&lt;/strong&gt; data where each variable has its own column and each observation its own row.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, what would you do when you encounter a ‚Äúnon-tidy‚Äù dataframe ?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://media.giphy.com/media/jDwbjzWljPUK4/giphy.gif&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You would surely consider using the &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/tidyverse/tidyr&#34;&gt;tidyr package&lt;/a&gt; which provides two important functions: &lt;code&gt;pivot_longer()&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;pivot_wider()&lt;/code&gt;. In this short tutorial, we‚Äôll introduce the &lt;code&gt;pivot_longer()&lt;/code&gt;. This function transforms several columns into a &lt;strong&gt;column name&lt;/strong&gt; and a &lt;strong&gt;column value&lt;/strong&gt;, thus making the dataframe longer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let‚Äôs dive into one example. We use the recent &lt;a href=&#34;https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/wpp2017/wpp2017.pdf&#34;&gt;wpp2017 package&lt;/a&gt; which provides several interesting datasets to work with. In our case, we‚Äôll work with the &lt;strong&gt;migration&lt;/strong&gt; data:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre class=&#34;r&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;library(tidyverse)
library(wpp2017)

data(&amp;quot;migration&amp;quot;)
head(migration)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
